{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13834"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.06,0.04,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6451"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2718"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive fatigue, weight loss of 5 kg, and darkening of her skin. She reports feeling dizzy when standing up quickly. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with vital signs as follows: pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg supine and 80/50 mmHg standing, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Skin examination is performed (Images 1-2). Investigations reveal sodium 130 mmol/L (135-145) and potassium 5.3 mmol/L (3.5-5.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urinary free cortisol","Thyroid function tests","CT scan of the adrenal glands","Oral glucose tolerance test","Serum cortisol and ACTH levels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs suggestive of Addison\u0027s disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency. The most appropriate next step in management is to measure \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum cortisol and ACTH levels\u003C/strong\u003E. These tests are essential for diagnosing Addison\u0027s disease and differentiating it from secondary adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Addison\u0027s disease, morning serum cortisol levels are typically low, while ACTH levels are elevated due to the lack of negative feedback. If the results are equivocal, an ACTH stimulation test may be necessary to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. It can be used in the diagnosis of diabetes mellitus, which is not suggested by the patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered later in the workup, as autoimmune thyroid disease can coexist with Addison\u0027s disease in polyglandular autoimmune syndromes. However, they are not the most appropriate next step given the clinical picture strongly suggestive of adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E test is more commonly used to diagnose Cushing\u0027s syndrome (cortisol excess) rather than adrenal insufficiency. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed later to investigate the aetiology of Addison\u0027s disease, particularly to rule out infectious or metastatic causes. However, it is not the most appropriate next step before confirming the diagnosis with hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce Addison\u0027s disease is confirmed, treatment typically involves lifelong replacement of glucocorticoids (e.g., hydrocortisone) and mineralocorticoids (e.g., fludrocortisone). Patient education about stress dosing and the need for medical alert identification is crucial for managing this chronic condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Addison\u0027s disease presents with fatigue, weight loss, hyperpigmentation, and postural hypotension.","Serum cortisol and ACTH levels are essential for diagnosing Addison\u0027s disease.","Treatment of Addison\u0027s disease involves glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid replacement."],"references":["O\u0027Connell S, Siafarikas A. Addison disease - diagnosis and initial management. Aust Fam Physician. 2010 Nov;39(11):834-7. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/29c07376-17dc-49b7-845d-f7aa753f6438/Addison-disease.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20782"},{"type":"media","id":"20783"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20782"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QYeBKocUiyDyV8h8iEt2NuAF0lgH8U.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.